value.0: This boulder rises from the ashes of the dead, as if suggesting some sort of memorial to the horror that has transpired here.
The wind blows cold about you and you shiver with the realization that you don't remember who these people were, or what drove them to this bitter end. A part of you begins to feel very, very alone.
<StartAction>[DC: 11]</Start> You take the stonecutter's chisel from your pack and steady your grip upon the hammer. You feel the sudden need to leave your mark upon this grisly place.
<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> Your first strokes are slow and awkward. Terrified of how it might turn out, you continue.
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> Your first strokes are swift and sure, the letters graceful. You continue with confidence.
Painstakingly, you etch the opening words into the stone.
The work is hard and slow, the chisel cold as ice within your grasp.

Wiping the sweat from your brow, you eye your work. It is too late to change it now.
Returning the chisel and hammer to your pack, you rise.
With the final strokes, you chisel in your name: "<FullName>."
The lettering is ragged, the lines slanted every which way. Even so, you can make out what it says:
The lettering, though simple, is clean and straight, obviously carved with great love and care. The lines are deep and visible, even from a fair distance.

You feel the weight of the stonecutter's chisel within your pack. If only you had something with which to hammer it.
A message has been etched into the stone's white face. Snow is beginning to collect in the cracks but the carving still seems quite recent.
<StartAction>[Dexterity]</Start> Carve a message into the rock.
"...of us being all loyal to the king..."
"...We all die but we win anyway."
"...and to that Prince guy we was following."
"...and to Prince Ahmed who we followed."
"...to the horror of the battle waged..."
"...and how good everybody was who fought it."
"...and the honor of those who waged it."
"...I have left to tell the king."
"...but me hunt down who kill him!"
"...I have left to find my king."
"...I have left to tell the king."
"...They dead but they help me survive."
